<h1 id="what-happens-during-deserialization">What happens during deserialization?</h1>

<p><img src="../../assets/img/image-20210415175008173.png" alt="image-20210415175008173" /></p>

<ol>
  <li>The object is <strong>read</strong> from the stream</li>
  <li>The JVM determines the object‚Äôs <strong>class type</strong></li>
  <li>The JVM attempts to <strong>find and load</strong> the object‚Äôs <strong>class</strong>. If the JVM can‚Äôt find and/or load the class,the JVM throws an exception and the deserialization fails</li>
  <li>A new object is given space on the heap,but the <strong>serialized object‚Äôs constructor does NOT run</strong>! Obviously,if the constructor ran,it would restore the state of the object back to its original ‚Äònew‚Äô state,and that‚Äôs not what we want. We want the object to be restored to the state it had when it was serialized,not when it was first created</li>
  <li>If the object has a non-serializable class somewhere up its inheritance tree,the <strong>constructor for that non-serializable class will run</strong> along with any constructors above that. Once the constructor chaining begins,you can‚Äôt stop it,which means all superclasses,begining with the first non-serializable one,will reinitialize their state</li>
  <li>The object‚Äôs <strong>instance variables are given the values from the serialized state</strong>. Transient variables are given a value of null for object reference and default for primitive</li>
</ol>

<h1 id="writing-a-string-to-a-text-file">Writing a String to a Text File</h1>

<p>Writing text data is similar to writing an object,except you write a String instead of an object,and you use a FileWriter instead of a FileOutputStream.</p>

<h3 id="to-write-a-serialized-object">To write a serialized object:</h3>

<div class="language-java highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="n">objectOutputStream</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">writeObject</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">someObject</span><span class="o">);</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><strong>To write a String:</strong></p>

<div class="language-java highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="n">fileWriter</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">write</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="s">"My first String to save"</span><span class="o">);</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

